output:
package main

templ Hello(name string) {
  <div>Hello, { name }</div>
}

templ Greeting(person Person) {
  <div class="greeting">
    @Hello(person.Name)
  </div>
}

Yes, outside of templ Components, templ files are ordinary Go code. For example:

```templ name="header.templ"
package main

// Ordinary Go code that we can use in our Component.
var greeting = "Welcome!"

// templ Component
templ headerTemplate(name string) {
  <header>
    <h1>{ name }</h1>
    <h2>"{ greeting }" comes from ordinary Go code</h2>
  </header>
}
```

You can set element attributes to Go strings using expressions. For example:
```templ
templ component(testID string) {
  <p data-testid={ testID }>Text</p>
}
templ page() {
  @component("testid-123")
}
```
The output will be:
```html
<p data-testid="testid-123">Text</p>
```

Spread attributes allow you to append a dynamic map of attributes to an element's attributes using the `{ attrMap... }` syntax. The map must be of type `templ.Attributes`, which is a `map[string]any`. Example:
```templ
templ component(shouldBeUsed bool, attrs templ.Attributes) {
  <p { attrs... }>Text</p>
  <hr
    if shouldBeUsed {
      { attrs... }
    }
  />
}
templ usage() {
  @component(false, templ.Attributes{"data-testid": "paragraph"}) 
}
```
The output will be:
```html
<p data-testid="paragraph">Text</p>
<hr>
```

JavaScript attributes like `onClick` expect a reference to a `script` template. This ensures that client-side JavaScript is emitted only once and avoids script name collisions. Example:
```templ
script withParameters(a string, b string, c int) {
	console.log(a, b, c);
}
script withoutParameters() {
	alert("hello");
}
templ Button(text string) {
	<button onClick={ withParameters("test", text, 123) } onMouseover={ withoutParameters() } type="button">{ text }</button>
}
```
The output will include the necessary `<script>` tags and event handlers.

To set an attribute's value to a JSON string (e.g., for HTMX or Alpine.js), you can serialize the value to a string using a Go function. Example:
```go
func countriesJSON() string {
	countries := []string{"Czech Republic", "Slovakia", "United Kingdom", "Germany", "Austria", "Slovenia"}
	bytes, _ := json.Marshal(countries)
	return string(bytes)
}
```
Then use it in your templ component:
```templ
templ SearchBox() {
	<search-webcomponent suggestions={ countriesJSON() } />
}
```

In templ, you can use Go control flow statements like `if`, `switch`, and `for` directly within elements to conditionally render child elements or iterate over variables. For example:
```templ
templ showHelloIfTrue(b bool) {
	<div>
		if b {
			<p>Hello</p>
		}
	</div>
}
```
This will render `<p>Hello</p>` only if `b` is `true`.

Templ will complain if a text run starts with `if`, `switch`, or `for` but no opening brace `{` is found. For example, the following code will cause an error:
```templ
templ showIfTrue(b bool) {
	if b 
	  <p>Hello</p>
	}
}
```
To resolve this, use a Go string expression or capitalize the keyword.

In templ, you can use standard Go `if`/`else` statements to conditionally render components and elements. For example:
```templ
templ login(isLoggedIn bool) {
  if isLoggedIn {
    <div>Welcome back!</div>
  } else {
    <input name="login" type="button" value="Log in"/>
  }
}
```
When rendered with `isLoggedIn` set to `true`, the output will be:
```html
<div>
 Welcome back!
</div>
```

In templ, you can use the `{{ ... }}` syntax to include raw Go code statements in your template. This is useful for advanced use cases, such as declaring scoped variables to reduce the need for multiple function calls. For example:
```templ
templ nameList(items []Item) {
    {{ first := items[0] }}
    <p>
        { first.Name }
    </p>
}
```
When rendered with a slice of items, the output will be:
```html
<p>A</p>
```

In templ, templates can be composed using the `@` syntax to call other templates. For example:
```templ
templ showAll() {
	@left()
	@middle()
	@right()
}
templ left() {
	<div>Left</div>
}
templ middle() {
	<div>Middle</div>
}
templ right() {
	<div>Right</div>
}
```
The output will be:
```html
<div>
 Left
</div>
<div>
 Middle
</div>
<div>
 Right
</div>
```

Children can be passed to a component using the `{ children... }` expression. For example:
```templ
templ showAll() {
	@wrapChildren() {
		<div>Inserted from the top</div>
	}
}
templ wrapChildren() {
	<div id="wrapper">
		{ children... }
	</div>
}
```
The output will be:
```html
<div id="wrapper">
 <div>
  Inserted from the top
 </div>
</div>
```

Components can be aggregated into a single component using `templ.Join`. For example:
```templ
templ helloWorld() {
	@templ.Join(hello(), world())
}
```
The output will be:
```html
<span>hello</span><span>world</span>
```

Since templ components are compiled into Go functions, they follow Go's rules for sharing and reusing code. Components in the same directory can access each other, and components in different directories can be accessed by importing the package containing the component. To export a component, capitalize its name. For example:
```templ
templ Hello() {
	<div>Hello</div>
}
```
To import and use it:
```templ
import "github.com/a-h/templ/examples/counter/components"
templ Home() {
	@components.Hello()
}
```

You can conditionally apply styles using the `templ.KV` helper, which allows compact syntax for conditional styling. For example:
```templ
templ TextInput(value string, hasError bool) {
    <input
        type="text"
        value={ value }
        style={
            templ.KV("border-color: #ff3860", hasError),
            templ.KV("background-color: #fff5f7", hasError),
            "padding: 0.5em 1em;",
        }
    >
}
```
If `hasError` is `true`, the styles will be applied.

By default, dynamic CSS values are sanitized to prevent vulnerabilities. To bypass sanitization, mark your content as safe using `templ.SafeCSS` or `templ.SafeCSSProperty`. For example:
```templ
func calculatePositionStyles(x, y int) templ.SafeCSS {
    return templ.SafeCSS(fmt.Sprintf(
        "transform: translate(%dpx, %dpx);",
        x*2, y*2,
    ))
}
templ DraggableElement(x, y int) {
    <div style={ calculatePositionStyles(x, y) }>
        Drag me
    </div>
}
```
The output will include the unsanitized CSS.

CSS components allow you to encapsulate styles within a component library. They ensure styles are rendered only once per HTTP request and generate unique class names. For example:
```templ
css primaryClassName() {
	background-color: #ffffff;
	color: { red };
}
templ button(text string, isPrimary bool) {
	<button class={ "button", primaryClassName(), templ.KV(primaryClassName(), isPrimary) }>{ text }</button>
}
```
The output includes a `<style>` block with unique class names:
```html
<style type="text/css">
 .className_f179{background-color:#ffffff;color:#ff0000;}
</style>
<button class="button className_f179">
 Click me
</button>
```

CSS components can accept arguments to dynamically generate styles. For example:
```templ
css loading(percent int) {
	width: { fmt.Sprintf("%d%%", percent) };
}
templ index() {
    <div class={ loading(50) }></div>
    <div class={ loading(100) }></div>
}
```
The output includes unique class names for each argument value:
```html
<style type="text/css">
 .loading_a3cc{width:50%;}
</style>
<div class="loading_a3cc"></div>
<style type="text/css">
 .loading_9ccc{width:100%;}
</style>
<div class="loading_9ccc"></div>
```

You can include JavaScript in templ components using standard `<script>` tags. For example:
```templ
templ body() {
  <script>
    function handleClick(event) {
      alert(event + ' clicked');
    }
  </script>
  <button onclick="handleClick(this)">Click me</button>
}
```
To ensure a `<script>` tag is rendered only once per HTTP response, use `templ.OnceHandle`.

You can pass server-side data to the client in a `<script>` element using `templ.JSONScript`. For example:
```templ
templ body(data any) {
  @templ.JSONScript("id", data)
}
```
The output will include the data in a `<script>` tag:
```html
<script id="id" type="application/json">{"msg":"Hello, from the script data"}</script>
```

To avoid inline event handlers, you can use a `<script>` tag to add client-side behavior dynamically. For example:
```templ
templ hello(label, name string) {
  @helloHandle.Once() {
    <script>
      function hello(name) {
        alert('Hello, ' + name + '!');
      }
    </script>
  }
  <div>
    <input type="button" value={ label } data-name={ name }/>
    <script>
      (() => {
        let scriptElement = document.currentScript;
        let parent = scriptElement.closest('div');
        let nearestButtonWithName = parent.querySelector('input[data-name]');
        nearestButtonWithName.addEventListener('click', function() {
          let name = nearestButtonWithName.getAttribute('data-name');
          hello(name);
        })
      })()
    </script>
  </div>
}
```

You can reduce boilerplate by using utility libraries like [surreal](https://github.com/gnat/surreal). For example:
```templ
templ hello(label, name string) {
  @surrealHandle.Once() {
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/gnat/surreal@3b4572dd0938ce975225ee598a1e7381cb64ffd8/surreal.js"></script>
  }
  <div>
    <input type="button" value={ label } data-name={ name }/>
    <script>
      me("-").addEventListener('click', function() {
        let name = this.getAttribute('data-name');
        hello(name);
      })
    </script>
  </div>
}
```
This approach simplifies event handling and reduces repetitive code.

Script templates are a legacy feature in templ that allow you to pass Go data to JavaScript. For example:
```templ
script graph(data []TimeValue) {
	const chart = LightweightCharts.createChart(document.body, { width: 400, height: 300 });
	const lineSeries = chart.addLineSeries();
	lineSeries.setData(data);
}
templ page(data []TimeValue) {
	<html>
		<head>
			<script src="https://unpkg.com/lightweight-charts/dist/lightweight-charts.standalone.production.js"></script>
		</head>
		<body onload={ graph(data) }></body>
	</html>
}
```
The `graph` function is called with JSON-encoded Go data when the page loads.

You can render JavaScript functions directly in templ using the `@` expression. For example:
```templ
script printToConsole(content string) {
	console.log(content)
}
templ page(content string) {
	<html>
		<body>
		  @printToConsole(content)
		  @printToConsole(fmt.Sprintf("Again: %s", content))
		</body>
	</html>
}
```
The output will include `<script>` tags that call the JavaScript function with JSON-encoded Go data:
```html
<script>__templ_printToConsole_5a85("2023-11-11 01:01:40.983381358 +0000 UTC")</script>
```

You can pass arbitrary JavaScript expressions to templ script templates using the `templ.JSExpression` type. A common use case is passing the `event` or `this` objects to an event handler. For example:
```templ
script showButtonWasClicked(event templ.JSExpression) {
	const originalButtonText = event.target.innerText;
	event.target.innerText = "I was Clicked!";
	setTimeout(() => event.target.innerText = originalButtonText, 2000);
}
templ page() {
	<html>
		<body>
			<button type="button" onclick={ showButtonWasClicked(templ.JSExpression("event")) }>Click Me</button>
		</body>
	</html>
}
```

Outside of templ statements, you can use standard Go comments. For example:
```templ
package main
// Use standard Go comments outside templ statements.
var greeting = "Hello!"
templ hello(name string) {
	<p>{greeting} { name }</p>
}
```
Go comments are not rendered in the output and are only visible in the source code.

To make context usage type-safe, implement a helper function that retrieves the value from the context. For example:
```go
func GetTheme(ctx context.Context) string {
	if theme, ok := ctx.Value(themeContextKey).(string); ok {
		return theme
	}
	return ""
}
```
Then use this function in your templ component:
```templ
templ themeName() {
	<div>{ GetTheme(ctx) }</div>
}
```
This approach avoids direct type assertions in templates and improves code readability.

You can use `context` with HTTP middleware to pass request-specific data to templ components. For example:
```go
func Middleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
	return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
		ctx := context.WithValue(r.Context(), contextClass, "red")
		next.ServeHTTP(w, r.WithContext(ctx))
	})
}
```
The middleware sets a context value, which can be accessed in templ components:
```templ
templ Show() {
	<div class={ ctx.Value(contextClass) }>Display</div>
}
```
This ensures the context value is available for the duration of the HTTP request.

To use React components with templ, follow these steps:
1. **Create React Components**: Write your React components using TSX or JSX.
   ```tsx
   export const Header = () => (<h1>React component Header</h1>);
   export const Body = () => (<div>This is client-side content from React</div>);
   ```
2. **Create a Templ Page**: Use templ to define HTML elements with specific IDs where React components will be rendered.
   ```templ
   templ page() {
       <html>
           <body>
               <div id="react-header"></div>
               <div id="react-content"></div>
               <script src="static/index.js"></script>
           </body>
       </html>
   }
   ```
3. **Render React Components**: Use JavaScript/TypeScript to render React components into the specified IDs.
   ```typescript
   import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client';
   import { Header, Body } from './components';
   const headerRoot = document.getElementById('react-header');
   if (!headerRoot) throw new Error('Could not find element with id react-header');
   const headerReactRoot = createRoot(headerRoot);
   headerReactRoot.render(Header());
   ```
4. **Bundle the Code**: Use a bundler like `esbuild` to create a client-side JavaScript bundle.
   ```bash
   esbuild --bundle index.ts --outdir=../static --minify
   ```

To pass server-side data to React components:
1. **Create a React Component**: Define a React component that accepts data as props.
   ```tsx
   export const Hello = (name: string) => (
     <div>Hello {name} (Client-side React, rendering server-side data)</div>
   );
   ```
2. **Export a Rendering Function**: Write a JavaScript function to render the React component into an HTML element, extracting data from attributes.
   ```typescript
   export function renderHello(e: HTMLElement) {
     const name = e.getAttribute('data-name') ?? "";
     createRoot(e).render(Hello(name));
   }
   ```
3. **Update the Templ Component**: Use templ to generate HTML elements with `data-*` attributes and include a `<script>` tag to call the rendering function.
   ```templ
   templ Hello(name string) {
       <div data-name={ name }>
           <script>
               bundle.renderHello(document.currentScript.closest('div'));
           </script>
       </div>
   }
   ```
4. **Bundle with `esbuild`**: Use `esbuild` with the `--global-name` flag to expose the rendering function globally.
   ```bash
   esbuild --bundle index.ts --outdir=../static --minify --global-name=bundle
   ```

To ensure content is rendered only once per page, use a `*OnceHandler` created with `templ.NewOnceHandle()` and its `Once()` method. For example:
```templ
var helloHandle = templ.NewOnceHandle()
templ hello(label, name string) {
  @helloHandle.Once() {
    <script>
      function hello(name) {
        alert('Hello, ' + name + '!');
      }
    </script>
  }
  <input type="button" value={ label } data-name={ name } onclick="hello(this.getAttribute('data-name'))"/>
}
```
Even if the `hello` component is rendered multiple times, the `<script>` block will only appear once in the output.

To share `*OnceHandler` components across packages, export the component containing the `*OnceHandler` from a shared package. For example, create a `deps` package with a `JQuery` component:
```templ
package deps
var jqueryHandle = templ.NewOnceHandle()
templ JQuery() {
  @jqueryHandle.Once() {
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
  }
}
```
Then, import and use the `JQuery` component in other packages to ensure the script is included only once:
```templ
@deps.JQuery()
```

Templ components are markup and code that are compiled into Go functions returning a `templ.Component` interface by running the `templ generate` command. For example:
```templ
templ headerTemplate(name string) {
  <header data-testid="headerTemplate">
    <h1>{ name }</h1>
  </header>
}
```
The generated Go function looks like this:
```go
func headerTemplate(name string) templ.Component {
  // Generated contents
}
```
The `templ.Component` interface includes a `Render` method to output the component's HTML to an `io.Writer`.

Method components are templ components attached to a type as methods. For example:
```templ
type Data struct {
	message string
}
templ (d Data) Method() {
	<div>{ d.message }</div>
}
```
You can call the method on an instance of the type:
```go
d := Data{message: "You can implement methods on a type."}
d.Method().Render(context.Background(), os.Stdout)
```
Alternatively, you can initialize the struct and call the method inline:
```templ
@Data{
    message: "You can implement methods on a type.",
}.Method()
```

In code-only components, you are responsible for escaping HTML content to prevent security vulnerabilities. Use the `templ.EscapeString` function to safely escape strings before rendering them. For example:
```go
func safeButton(text string) templ.Component {
	escapedText := templ.EscapeString(text)
	return templ.ComponentFunc(func(ctx context.Context, w io.Writer) error {
		_, err := io.WriteString(w, "<button>" + escapedText + "</button>")
		return err
	})
}
```

Expectation testing validates that specific data appears in the output in the correct format and position. You can use the `goquery` library to parse and query the HTML output of a templ component. For example:
```go
func TestHeader(t *testing.T) {
    r, w := io.Pipe()
    go func() {
        _ = headerTemplate("Posts").Render(context.Background(), w)
        _ = w.Close()
    }()
    doc, err := goquery.NewDocumentFromReader(r)
    if err != nil {
        t.Fatalf("failed to read template: %v", err)
    }
    if doc.Find(`[data-testid="headerTemplate"]`).Length() == 0 {
        t.Error("expected data-testid attribute to be rendered, but it wasn't")
    }
}
```
This approach ensures that specific elements and attributes are present in the rendered output.

To test navigation items, use `goquery` to find all `a` elements within the `nav` element and verify their content matches expected values. For example:
```go
navItems := []string{"Home", "Posts"}
doc.Find("nav a").Each(func(i int, s *goquery.Selection) {
    expected := navItems[i]
    if actual := s.Text(); actual != expected {
        t.Errorf("expected nav item %q, got %q", expected, actual)
    }
})
```
This ensures the navigation bar contains the correct links and labels.

To test HTTP handlers, use the `httptest` package to create a test server and make requests to it. For example:
```go
func TestPostsHandler(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name           string
        postGetter     func() ([]Post, error)
        expectedStatus int
        assert         func(doc *goquery.Document)
    }{
        {
            name: "database errors result in a 500 error",
            postGetter: func() ([]Post, error) {
                return nil, errors.New("database error")
            },
            expectedStatus: http.StatusInternalServerError,
            assert: func(doc *goquery.Document) {
                if doc.Text() != "failed to retrieve posts\n" {
                    t.Errorf("expected error message")
                }
            },
        },
    }
    for _, test := range tests {
        w := httptest.NewRecorder()
        r := httptest.NewRequest(http.MethodGet, "/posts", nil)
        ph := NewPostsHandler()
        ph.GetPosts = test.postGetter
        ph.ServeHTTP(w, r)
        doc, _ := goquery.NewDocumentFromReader(w.Result().Body)
        test.assert(doc)
    }
}
```
This approach tests both error handling and successful rendering of posts.

Snapshot testing checks that the output of a component hasn't changed since the last time a snapshot was taken. It relies on manually verifying the output initially and then comparing future outputs against the saved snapshot. For example:
```go
func Test(t *testing.T) {
    component := render("sample content")
    diff, err := htmldiff.Diff(component, expected)
    if err != nil {
        t.Fatal(err)
    }
    if diff != "" {
        t.Error(diff)
    }
}
```
This ensures consistency in rendering and helps detect unintended changes.

View models in templ are Go structs that contain only the fields needed for rendering a template. They simplify testing by decoupling the data structure from complex backend logic, making it easier to test templates in isolation. Instead of passing raw data or complex structures directly into templates, you create a view model that closely matches the visual layout. For example:

```go
type InviteComponentViewModel struct {
  InviteCount  int
  ErrorMessage string
}
```
This approach avoids calling APIs or performing complex transformations within templates, reducing the need for integration tests. The handler prepares the view model, and the template focuses on rendering:
```templ
templ teamInviteComponent(model InviteComponentViewModel) {
  if model.InviteCount > 0 {
    <div>You have { fmt.Sprintf("%d", model.InviteCount) } pending invites</div>
  }
  if model.ErrorMessage != "" {
    <div class="error">{ model.ErrorMessage }</div>
  }
}
```
This ensures templates are easier to test and maintain.

Good templ components should be idempotent and pure functions, meaning they rely only on their parameters and produce the same output for the same inputs. Avoid embedding logic like `time.Now()` directly in components; instead, pass dynamic data as parameters. This ensures reusability and testability. For example:
```templ
templ timeComponent(d time.Time) {
    <div>{ d.String() }</div>
}
```

To set up templ in Visual Studio Code, install the templ extension from the marketplace (https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=a-h.templ). Ensure that the `templ` CLI is installed and available in your system path. You can enable formatting on save by adding the following to your `settings.json`:
```json
{
    "editor.formatOnSave": true,
    "[templ]": {
        "editor.defaultFormatter": "a-h.templ"
    }
}
```

To enable Tailwind CSS autocompletion for `.templ` files in VS Code, add the following to your `settings.json`:
```json
{
  "tailwindCSS.includeLanguages": {
    "templ": "html"
  }
}
```
Ensure that a `tailwind.config.js` file exists in your project root. If not, create one using `npx tailwindcss init`.

To integrate other LSPs with `.templ` files in Neovim, configure their `filetypes` to include `templ`. For example:
- **Tailwind CSS**:
```lua
lspconfig.tailwindcss.setup({
    filetypes = { "templ", "html" },
    settings = {
        tailwindCSS = {
            includeLanguages = {
                templ = "html",
            },
        },
    },
})
```
- **HTMX**:
```lua
lspconfig.htmx.setup({
    filetypes = { "templ", "html" },
})
```
Ensure your `tailwind.config.js` includes `.templ` files in its `content` array.

In templ, `on*` attributes (e.g., `onClick`) accept a `templ.ComponentScript` instead of raw strings. This ensures that any JavaScript executed is properly escaped and safe. For example:
```html
script onClickHandler(msg string) {
  alert(msg);
}
templ Example(msg string) {
  <div onClick={ onClickHandler(msg) }></div>
}
```
This approach prevents unescaped user data from being injected into the attribute.
